                              throughout.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>In poor condition, with extensive water and insect damage, with historical repairs throughout.</condition>
                                           </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="21" n="mistara">Written in 1 column,
                           with 21 lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">maṣṭārah</hi> hand guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nastaliq" medium="ink">Written primarily in a clear naskh hand tending towards nasta‘liq in <material>black</material>, with subheaders in
                        <material>red</material>, by <persName type="standard" role="scr">Ḥusayn ibn Hasan</persName>.</handNote>
                     <handNote scope="minor" script="nastaliq" medium="ink">missing portions and infilles written primarily in a hasty nasta‘liq script shikastah ligatures in <material>black</material>, apparently by the same hand that completed <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6656"
                        ><idno>Persian MS 173</idno></ref>.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1804" notAfter="1818">
                        <p>Probably bound in <country
                           cert="high" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/135375457">India</country> in full brown goatskin <material>leather</material> in two separate pieces that overlap on the spine.</p> 
                        <decoNote type="binding">
                           <p>Boards uniformly decorated together with the other volumes as a set,
                              with <material>paper</material> onlays for the central
                              scalloped mandorlas, detached pendants, and corners with the boards ruled in <material>white</material>.
                              Paper label on the spine bears the title of the volume in Persian.</p></decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                           <height>304</height>
                           <width>192</width>
                           <depth>85</depth>
                        </dimensions>
                        </p>
                        <condition>Handle with caution. In poor condition, with <locus from="front_board" to="front_board">right board</locus> pulling away from the spine, otherwise loose sewing, and the text block split between folios <locus from="104" to="105">104 and 105</locus>, exterior binding joints breaking. Boxed.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin><origPlace cert="medium">Probably <country
                     cert="high" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/135375457">India</country></origPlace> with a partial date of <q xml:lang="en">Sunday, 3 Ẕī-l-Ḥijjah</q> that omits the year.</origin>
                  <provenance><p> Likely either restored for, or obtained by <persName type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/19247044" key="19247044">Jonathan Duncan</persName>, who governed Bombay (Mumbai) for sixteen years.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Apparently subsequently acquired in <country
                     cert="high" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/135375457">India</country> by <persName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/32750828" key="person_32750828">Sir Graves Champney Haughton (1788–1849)</persName>, an early student at Fort William College who excelled in the study of several oriental languages, as per his inscription on folio <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus> dated <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1818-02">Feb. 1818</date>.
                  </p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Later owned by Persian scholar <persName type="standard"
                     role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923"
                     >Nathaniel Bland (1803–1865)</persName>, after whose death <settlement
                        type="city" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/261467287">London</settlement>
                     antiquarian dealer <persName type="standard" role="bsl"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                        (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                              >1866</date>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                        >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                              Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                        >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/"> John Rylands
                              Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
